  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">LWF - Transitional Shelters and Livelihood Recovery</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1,000 affected households whose homes have been destroyed by the earthquake to be equipped with safe and weather proof transitional shelters and access to toilets.  

1,000 affected households have adopted livelihood recovery activities (about 50% of these will be from the above households)</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Identification of 1000 households (from priority target groups: (i) women-headed (ii) households with disabled or chronically ill members (iii) households made up of solely elderly members (iv) Dalit (v) Indigenous Minority (v) ultra-poor households depending solely on daily wage labour and (vi) other minority and disadvantaged groups) 	
2. Distribution of transitional shelter kits (CGI sheets, umbrella nails, assorted hardened nails)	
3. Provide training to masons at VDC level 
4. Issuing of vouchers to the above selected households which can be exchanged for cash grants (for labour, tarpaulin, pit latrine and sanitation kit) from local banking institution - approx. 50% of the households receiving shelter materials	
5. Continuous monitoring of cash grant use	

1,000 affected households have adopted livelihood recovery activities (about 50% of these will be from the above households)
6. Selection of households for each liverlihood recovery activities 	
7. Conduct trainings (traditional skills, farming technologies)
8. Provide voucher (cash for work) (to those whose livelihoods are dependent on wage labor) for construction of the irrigation infrastructures
9. Provide startup support through seed money to target groups</narrative>
  </description>
